wept the Fair with Grief and Rage oppressed ; Strange Passions laboured in her pensive Breast ; She lost her Crook — her Flocks no more were told , And her Lambs wandered from their nightly Fold , Till to these Shades she took her desperate Way , And vowed no more to see the Beams of Day : Here the gay Roses on her Cheek expired , And from her Eyes the laughing Loves retired : No flowery Wreaths her faded Temples knew , Her Locks uncombed upon her Shoulders flew ; No silken Vestments on her Limbs were rolled , A russet Mantle saved her from the Cold ; A simple Cordage round her Waste she tied , And a rude Staff her better Hand supplied .
